oting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lea","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."],"variants":[{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Warin","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old name. The same as Waring or Guerin, who came over with the Conqueror; a name probably connected with that of the Waernas or Wernas. the Varini or Verini, a people of the Elbe"],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Warin de Lea de Lancaster Royal Falconer was born about 1116, in Kendal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom as the son of Gilbert LANCASTER FITZKETEL de Tallenbois Baron Kendal. He had at least 2 sons. He died about 1191, in his hometown, at the age of 77."},"et":{"about 1116–about 1191":"umbes 1116–umbes 1191","1116–1191":"1116–1191","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1104–1170":"1104–1170","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","1158":"1158","about 1191":"umbes 1191","about 1116":"umbes 1116","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1208":"1208","1191":"1191","Kendal, Westmoreland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kendal Castle, Westmoreland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1116–about 1191":"noin 1116–noin 1191","1116–1191":"1116–1191","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1104–1170":"1104–1170","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","1158":"1158","about 1191":"noin 1191","about 1116":"noin 1116","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1208":"1208","1191":"1191","Kendal, Westmoreland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kendal Castle, Westmoreland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1116–about 1191":"environ 1116–environ 1191","1116–1191":"1116–1191","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1104–1170":"1104–1170","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","1158":"1158","about 1191":"environ 1191","about 1116":"environ 1116","1140":"1140","1170":"1170